{
  "ADUs": {
    "ADU1": {
      "text": "My aim in this paper is to show that a plausible account of how thoughts get their contents (a solution to the problem of 'cognitive contact') cannot explain how desires get their contents.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU2": {
      "text": "The account in question says that to have an occurrent thought is to perform an act of predication, and that thoughts have the contents they do because we perform acts of predication that individuate those contents.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU3": {
      "text": "I argue that performing an act of predication is not a necessary condition on having an occurrent desire, and that having an occurrent desire is not an act of predication.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU4": {
      "text": "At the very least this raises a question about how such attitudes make contact with propositions.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU5": {
      "text": "This also makes significant trouble for the act theory of content, which holds that propositions are types of activities we perform when we speak and think.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU6": {
      "text": "Act-theoretic accounts of content hold that propositions are structured entities whose constituents are cognitive acts that individuate objects and properties (acts of referring to objects and expressing properties).",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU7": {
      "text": "Though their views differ in several crucial respects, both Hanks and Soames agree that propositions are identical to acts of predication, whereby an agent combines reference to an object and expression of a property.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU8": {
      "text": "Taking propositions to be cognitive acts means holding that our basic cognitive contact with propositions comes via a particular type of occurrent mental activity.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU9": {
      "text": "In what follows, I argue that an act theory of content in particular - but also anyone who endorses the view that cognitive contact is a matter of predication will have significant difficulty explaining the intentionality of bouletic attitudes, like desiring, hoping, and wanting.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU10": {
      "text": "The reason for this is that an agent can undergo such attitudes without any particular act of predication being performed.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU11": {
      "text": "One of the central claims of the act theory of content is that intentional mental activity has the content it does in virtue of an act of predication (where one combines object and property in thought) being performed.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU12": {
      "text": "But not all intentional mental activity with propositional content seems to involve combining objects with properties in thought.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU13": {
      "text": "To undergo an occurrent desire is to undergo mental activity with a particular intentionality.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU14": {
      "text": "To undergo an occurrent desire that p is to undergo mental activity with the intentionality p, and thus for the act theorist it is to perform an act of predication which individuates p.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU15": {
      "text": "In this section I argue that the act theory of propositions cannot explain how occurrent desires have propositional content: it is possible to come up with cases of occurrent desire which are such that it is clear that the occurrent desire has a content, but it is not clear how this can be explained by an act of predication.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU16": {
      "text": "If a desire has a content p but p is not performed by the agent undergoing that desire, then cognitive contact does not come through the performance of p.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU17": {
      "text": "What does it take for me to undergo an occurrent desire with the (representational) content that the window is closed? It does not take predication involving that proposition.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU18": {
      "text": "If I believe that the window is open, and I believe that this state of affairs is the cause of my being cold, and being cold feels bad to me, then this seems to suffice.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU19": {
      "text": "Any consideration of what I want - via an act of predication - seems necessarily to be manifesting, in thought, a consideration of my already present desire.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU20": {
      "text": "What this case shows is that there is no act of predication (Soames' entertaining / Hanks' judging) in which the desire consists.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU21": {
      "text": "Desiring something does not require us to combine the aims of our actions in thought: I do not need to have a thought about the window's being closed or a thought about myself being warm.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU22": {
      "text": "If I do have such thoughts, it seems clear that they do not constitute the desire.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU23": {
      "text": "I have raised an issue for the claim that our cognitive contact with propositions always comes via an act of predication; i.e., combining object and property in thought.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU24": {
      "text": "On behalf of the propositionalist, I have also pointed out that cognitive contact can be a manifestation of our affective as well as our cognitive capacities.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU25": {
      "text": "This does not require us to perform an act whereby we mentally combine the object and property.",
      "label": "premise"
    }
  },
